  779:   3: description: "Use when the user asks about GitNexus itself — available tools, how to query the knowledge graph, MCP resources, graph schema, or workflow reference. Examples: \"What GitNexus tools are available?\", \"How do I use GitNexus?\""
  780:   4: ---
  781:   5: 
  782:   6: # GitNexus Guide
  783:   7: 
  784:   8: Quick reference for all GitNexus MCP tools, resources, and the knowledge graph schema.
  785:   9: 
  786:  10: ## Always Start Here
  787:  11: 
  788:  12: For any task involving code understanding, debugging, impact analysis, or refactoring:
  789:  13: 
  790:  14: 1. **Read `gitnexus://repo/{name}/context`** — codebase overview + check index freshness
  791:  15: 2. **Match your task to a skill below** and **read that skill file**
  792:  16: 3. **Follow the skill's workflow and checklist**
  793:  17: 
  794:  18: > If step 1 warns the index is stale, run `node .gitnexus/run.cjs analyze` in the terminal first.
  795:  19: 
  796:  20: ## Skills
  797:  21: 
  798:  22: | Task                                         | Skill to read       |
  799:  23: | -------------------------------------------- | ------------------- |
  800:  24: | Understand architecture / "How does X work?" | `gitnexus-exploring`         |
  801:  25: | Blast radius / "What breaks if I change X?"  | `gitnexus-impact-analysis`   |
  802:  26: | Trace bugs / "Why is X failing?"             | `gitnexus-debugging`         |
  803:  27: | Rename / extract / split / refactor          | `gitnexus-refactoring`       |
  804:  28: | Tools, resources, schema reference           | `gitnexus-guide` (this file) |
  805:  29: | Index, status, clean, wiki CLI commands      | `gitnexus-cli`               |
  806:  30: 
  807:  31: ## Tools Reference
  808:  32: 
  809:  33: | Tool             | What it gives you                                                        |
  810:  34: | ---------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------------------ |
  811:  35: | `query`          | Process-grouped code intelligence — execution flows related to a concept |
  812:  36: | `context`        | 360-degree symbol view — categorized refs, processes it participates in  |
  813:  37: | `impact`         | Symbol blast radius — what breaks at depth 1/2/3 with confidence         |
  814:  38: | `trace`          | Shortest path between two symbols — "how does A reach B?" in one call     |
  815:  39: | `detect_changes` | Git-diff impact — what do your current changes affect                    |
  816:  40: | `rename`         | Multi-file coordinated rename with confidence-tagged edits               |
  817:  41: | `cypher`         | Raw graph queries (read `gitnexus://repo/{name}/schema` first)           |
  818:  42: | `explain`        | Persisted taint findings — source→sink data flows (needs `analyze --pdg`) |
  819:  43: | `pdg_query`      | Control/data dependence — what gates X (CDG) / where Y flows (REACHING_DEF); needs `analyze --pdg` |
  820:  44: | `check`          | Check graph invariants such as circular imports                          |
  821:  45: | `list_repos`     | Discover indexed repos (paginated — `limit`/`offset`)                    |
  822:  46: 
  823:  47: ### Paginating `list_repos`
  824:  48: 
  825:  49: `list_repos` is paginated so a large registry is not truncated by MCP/LLM token limits. It takes optional `limit` (default **50**, max **200**) and `offset`, and returns:
  826:  50: 
  827:  51: ```jsonc
  828:  52: {
  829:  53:   "repositories": [
  830:  54:     { "name": "...", "path": "...", "indexedAt": "...", "lastCommit": "...", "stats": { } }
  831:  55:   ],
  832:  56:   "pagination": {
  833:  57:     "total": 437,
  834:  58:     "limit": 50,
  835:  59:     "offset": 0,
  836:  60:     "returned": 50,
  837:  61:     "hasMore": true,
  838:  62:     "nextOffset": 50
  839:  63:   }
  840:  64: }
  841:  65: ```
  842:  66: 
  843:  67: To enumerate **every** repository, keep calling with `offset` set to `pagination.nextOffset` until `hasMore` is `false`:
  844:  68: 
  845:  69: ```text
  846:  70: list_repos {}               → repos 1–50,    nextOffset 50,  hasMore true
  847:  71: list_repos { offset: 50 }   → repos 51–100,  nextOffset 100, hasMore true
  848:  72: …
  849:  73: list_repos { offset: 400 }  → repos 401–437,                 hasMore false   (done)
  850:  74: ```
  851:  75: 
  852:  76: Notes: `offset` ≥ `total` returns an empty page (with `total` still reported). Out-of-range or malformed `limit`/`offset` (non-integer, `limit` outside `[1, 200]`, `offset < 0`) are rejected with a clear error — `limit` above the max is rejected, not silently capped. The order is deterministic (lower-cased name, then path), so paging never skips or duplicates an entry while the registry is unchanged.
  853:  77: 
  854:  78: ### Taint findings (`explain`)
  855:  79: 
  856:  80: `explain` returns intra-procedural taint findings (`TAINTED` edges) recorded by `gitnexus analyze --pdg` — each with a sink category (command-injection, code-injection, path-traversal, sql-injection, xss), source/sink lines, and the ordered hop path with the variable carried on each hop.
  857:  81: 
  858:  82: - `explain {}` — enumerate all findings for the repo (bounded by `limit`, deterministic order)
  859:  83: - `explain { target: "src/vuln.ts" }` — findings in a file (suffix path match accepted)
  860:  84: - `explain { target: "runUserCommand" }` — findings in a function (resolved like `context`; ambiguous names return ranked candidates)
  861:  85: 
  862:  86: A repo indexed without `--pdg` returns a clear "no taint layer" note. Caveats: findings are intra-procedural only — cross-function, closure/callback, property/field, and implicit flows are not modeled, so the absence of a finding is **not** proof of safety. `SANITIZES` (sanitizer-kill) edges are queryable via `cypher`.
  863:  87: 
  864:  88: ### Control & data dependence (`pdg_query`)
  865:  89: 
  866:  90: `pdg_query` reads the control/data-dependence layers `gitnexus analyze --pdg` records (CDG + REACHING_DEF, basic-block granular) — the control/data analog of `explain`. It is **always anchored** (a `target` file path or symbol, resolved like `context`) and has two modes:
  867:  91: 
  868:  92: - `pdg_query { mode: "controls", target: "..." }` — CDG: "under what condition does X run?". Each edge is a controlling predicate block → dependent block with the branch sense (`'T'`/`'F'`) in `reason`; an edge into an early `return`/`throw` is flagged `guard: true` (guard-clause discovery — the sense depends on the predicate, so don't filter guards by a fixed label).
  869:  93: - `pdg_query { mode: "flows", target: "...", variable?: "..." }` — REACHING_DEF def→use edges within the function; pass `variable` to trace one binding.
  870:  94: 
  871:  95: A repo indexed without `--pdg` returns a "no PDG layer" note (or "status unknown" when the layer can't be confirmed). Intra-procedural only — cross-function flow is taint's domain (`explain`). The raw CDG/REACHING_DEF edges are also queryable via `cypher`. See the `gitnexus-pdg-query` skill for the full query surface.
  872:  96: 
  873:  97: ### Shortest path between two symbols (`trace`)
  874:  98: 
  875:  99: `trace` answers "how does A reach B?" in one call — the shortest directed path over `CALLS` (plus `HAS_METHOD`, so a class-rooted trace descends into its methods) instead of chaining 3–8 `context`/`impact` hops by hand.
  876: 100: 
  877: 101: - `trace { from: "validateUser", to: "executeQuery" }` — shortest path between two symbols.
  878: 102: - Disambiguate common names with `from_uid`/`to_uid` (zero-ambiguity) or `from_file`/`to_file`; an ambiguous name returns ranked candidates.
  879: 103: - `maxDepth` (default 10, max 30) bounds the search; `includeTests` (default false) lets the traversal pass through test-file symbols.
  880: 104: 
  881: 105: Returns ordered `hops` (each `{ name, filePath, startLine }`) and an aligned `edges[]` of `{ relType, confidence }`, so call hops and containment (`HAS_METHOD`) hops stay distinguishable. When no path exists it reports the **furthest** reachable node (where the chain breaks) and sets `truncated: true` if a traversal cap was hit first. Every result carries a `status`: `ok` / `no_path` / `ambiguous` / `not_found` / `error`.
  882: 106: 
  883: 107: ## Resources Reference
  884: 108: 
  885: 109: Lightweight reads (~100-500 tokens) for navigation:
  886: 110: 
  887: 111: | Resource                                       | Content                                   |
  888: 112: | ---------------------------------------------- | ----------------------------------------- |
  889: 113: | `gitnexus://repo/{name}/context`               | Stats, staleness check                    |
  890: 114: | `gitnexus://repo/{name}/clusters`              | All functional areas with cohesion scores |
  891: 115: | `gitnexus://repo/{name}/cluster/{clusterName}` | Area members                              |
  892: 116: | `gitnexus://repo/{name}/processes`             | All execution flows                       |
  893: 117: | `gitnexus://repo/{name}/process/{processName}` | Step-by-step trace                        |
  894: 118: | `gitnexus://repo/{name}/schema`                | Graph schema for Cypher                   |
  895: 119: 
  896: 120: ## Graph Schema
  897: 121: 
  898: 122: **Nodes:** File, Function, Class, Interface, Method, Community, Process
  899: 123: **Edges (via CodeRelation.type):** CALLS, IMPORTS, EXTENDS, IMPLEMENTS, DEFINES, MEMBER_OF, STEP_IN_PROCESS
  900: 124: 
  901: 125: ```cypher
  902: 126: MATCH (caller)-[:CodeRelation {type: 'CALLS'}]->(f:Function {name: "myFunc"})
  903: 127: RETURN caller.name, caller.filePath
  904: 128: ```
  905: </file>
